dataIdInfo.idPurp: In 2006, TNC sought to develop a classification of watershed units to be used in conservation planning and conservation measures benchmarks in South America. The objectives of this project were to: Map freshwater ecological systems at a continental scale for priority setting and conservation strategy planning, build freshwater-related datasets for reference and to have a standardized dataset to perform analysis and perform parallel analyses related to threats assessments, protected area gap analyses and other applications. The process that we followed aimed to replicate the classification methodology proposed by Higgins et al, 2005 (Figure 1). Using this hierarchical classification system, large classification units known as ecoregions and medium sized classification units known as Ecological Drainage Units, were mapped by a team of scientists in the effort published as Abel et al, 2008. The next logical step was to classify Freshwater Ecological Systems (a.k.a. Ecosystems). The Higgins et al, 2005 document presents the classification system, but not the methodology to develop the data or the classification. Because of this, we tested several options to generate the units we would use to run the classification of ecosystems. We tested the Hydrosheds (Lehner, 2008) classification system, but there was no connectivity among the units to work with this system. We tested generating watersheds at one size scale, but this only gave us one dimension of the units we needed. We then tested the Nested Sized Watershed Units Model developed by Fitzhugh (2005, see Appendix 1). Basically, this system generates watersheds at different sizes defined by the user. Once these units have been generated, we simply combined the different sizes to generate one dataset that uses attribute codes to differentiate the different sizes. We then proceeded to attribute these watershed units with geo-physical data and run a classification algorithm to find similarities among the geo-physical characteristics.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
To prepare our datasets we used the Hydrosheds (Lehner, 2008) 450 meter resolution digital elevation model (DEM) to generate Flowdirection, Flowaccumulation and a Raster Stream Network.

We followed the ESRI ArcINFO AML that Fitzhugh (2005) developed to create watersheds with user-defined sizes. Based on existing research (ecoregional plans) and recommendations from experts (Bryer, 2006), we used the following size ranges to run the ArcINFO AML: 100 –1,000 Square KM –SIZE 1, 1,000 –10,000 Square KM –SIZE 2, 10,000 –100,000 Square KM –SIZE 3, 100,000 –1,000,000 Square KM –SIZE 4 and 1,000,000 –10,000,000 Square KM –SIZE 5.

In this mapping project, we generated all 5 sizes for the continent. An additional advantage of the Fitzhugh (2005) method is that we are able to place different size watershed units on top of each other and begin to see in a nested fashion how smaller watershed units contribute to the larger units.

Within the same basin, when we combine the watershed units, we can delineate contributions of smaller watershed units. In the case of SIZE4 + SIZE3 example, a larger river channel watershed is created and we can visualize and calculate (area estimated runoff, etc) of the contributing watersheds. The combination was done using the ESRI ARCINFO UNION command, one size layer at a time. Once all of the watershed unit sizes are combined, we can easily see the area of influence of each size category and we can follow drainage from any point in the basin to the main channel of the basin.

Each watershed unit in their different sizes has been coded with a unique ID number. When we combined all the sizes we maintained an attribute column with the SIZE ID numbers so the final layer with all the sizes contained all the information to be able to separate each different size class back to its original layer. For instance, if you need to extract the SIZE 2 layer from a watershed unit with all of its unit sizes combined, you simply have to run the DISSOLVE command in ARCINFO or ARCGIS using the SIZE2 ID attribute. Since we have combined these layers and they are both hydrologically and topologically correct, we can also extract specific features in the combined layer. For instance, the Main stem of a basin, where the main channel river passes, can be easily extracted from this topology. Each one of these features were attributed in an aim to classify what we can interpret as ecological systems, based on similar characteristics in terms of geo-physical attributes related to abiotic processes that characterize each system type and seve as a proxi to represent potential freshwater biotic heterogeneity.

References

Bryer, Mark. 2006. Personal Communication. The Nature Conservancy.

FitzHugh, Thomas W. 2005. GIS Tools for Freshwater Biodiversity Conservation Planning. Transactions in GIS, Vol: 9, No: 2, Pages: 247-263. The Nature Conservancy, Olympia, Washington http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-9671.2005.00215.x

Higgins, Jonathan V., Mark T. Bryer, Mary L. Khoury and Thomas W. Fitzhugh. 2005. A Freshwater Classification Approach For Biodiversity Conservation Planning. Conservation Biology, vol. 19, no2, pp. 432-445. The Nature Conservancy.

Lehner, B., K. Verdin, A. Jarvis. 2008. New Global Hydrography Derived From Spaceborne Elevation Data. Eos, Transactions, AGU, 89(10): 93-94. http://www.worldwildlife.org/science/projects/freshwater/item1991.html and http://hydrosheds.cr.usgs.gov/
